<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-06-25T10:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-06-25T10:00:00-05:00" n="653" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d653">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/1905</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GJW1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gerard</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-06-25T16:00:00+01:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">June 25, 1915, 4 p. m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received June 26, 4.30 p.
                                    m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>2494. The suspension of the newspaper reported in my 2469,<note n="1" xml:id="d653fn1">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_450">p.
                                    450</ref>.</note> has been severely criticized and the paper is
                                now permitted to appear again. The gagging of the press is resented
                                everywhere. Conservative and clerical papers side with the <hi rend="italic">Tageszeitung</hi> and deprecate the publication of
                                evidently inspired articles like that in <hi rend="italic">Lokal-Anzeiger</hi>, referred to in my 2426<note n="2" xml:id="d653fn2">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_441">p.
                                    441</ref>.</note> and 2451,<note n="3" xml:id="d653fn3">Not
                                    printed.</note> maintaining that this is a falsification of
                                public opinion in Germany which does not want war with America but
                                will not approve of any understanding with America at the cost of
                                any concessions which would impair the efficiency of the submarines.
                                The impression seems to prevail that the conciliatory articles
                                originated in official circles and it is feared that they will
                                weaken the position of the German negotiations.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="#p_GJW1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gerard</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>